properties.INFO: In the Vienna area the connection between the legion camps Vindobona and Carnuntum is called Limes Street. Their course within today's urban area is reconstructed as follows: coming from the auxiliary camp Klosterneuburg along the Danube, from Nudorfer Platz - Dblinger Hauptstrae - Whringer Strae - Votivkirche Schottengasse - Herrengasse - Augustinerstrae - Knstlerhaus - Rennweg - Simmeringer Hauptstrae (?), then leading towards the auxiliary camp Schwechat.

From the Roman road network until now only the thoroughfares are secured. In addition to actually discovered pieces of road, milestones also provide evidence for the course of the roads. In addition to the Limes road another exit road led from the porta principalis dextra on the Wollzeile, the Weikirchnerstrae and the Landstrasser main road to the east in the direction of civil society in today's third district. It ended in the area of today's Rennweg in the Limesstrae. At the height of the Votive Church, a road branched off from the Limes road to the porta principalis sinistra of the legionary camp. To the west this road led in the direction of today's districts Hernals and Ottakring, where Roman burial grounds and the Legionsziegeleien were. Another branch to the northeast could be found under the Palais Harrach. An intersection with the Limesstrae was finally detected at Michaelerplatz. This road formed the continuation of the via decumana and continued as a remote connection to Scarbantia (Sopron). Another highway to the south is occupied by several milestones in Inzersdorf.

One of the main axes in the road system of the Roman legion camp, namely the connection between the porta principalis sinistra (western camp gate) and the porta principalis dextra (eastern camp gate).

During the construction of the U3 extension to Simmering, a section of a forerunner of Simmeringer Hauptstrae was uncovered in 1997. This was called before 1894 "Preburger Postchaussee". According to the find material from the road route this piece of road may have been used between the late Middle Ages and the 18th century.
Connecting road from the principia (command building) in the middle of the camp to the porta decumana (southern camp gate).

Another branch to the northeast could be found under the Palais Harrach. An intersection with the Limesstrae was finally detected at Michaelerplatz. This road formed the continuation of the via decumana and continued as a remote connection to Scarbantia (Sopron). Another highway to the south is occupied by several milestones in Inzersdorf.
